ing model expectation of protecting wilderness via intensified agriculture is highlighted.}, chapter = {Biological Sciences}, copyright = {\textcopyright{} 2018 . http://www.pnas.org/site/aboutpnas/licenses.xhtmlPublished under the PNAS license.}, file = {/home/kristine/Zotero/storage/VUJVDHCB/Pellegrini and Fernández - 2018 - Crop intensification, land use, and on-farm energy.pdf;/home/kristine/Zotero/storage/XBBTNBCJ/2335.html}, journal = {Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences}, keywords = {EROI,Jevons paradox,land sharing,land sparing,water–energy–food security nexus}, language = {en}, number = {10}, pmid = {29463755} } @article{ray_recent_2012, title = {Recent Patterns of Crop Yield Growth and Stagnation}, author = {Ray, Deepak K. and Ramankutty, Navin and Mueller, Nathaniel D. and West, Paul C. and Foley, Jonathan A.}, year = {2012}, month = dec, volume = {3}, pages = {1293}, issn = {2041-1723}, doi = {10.1038/ncomms2296}, abstract = {In the coming decades, continued population growth, rising meat and dairy consumption and expanding biofuel use will dramatically increase the pressure on global agriculture. Even as we face these future burdens, there have been scattered reports of yield stagnation in the world's major cereal crops, including maize, rice and wheat. Here we study data from {$\sim$}2.5 million census observations across the globe extending over the period 1961\textendash 2008. We examined the trends in crop yields for four key global crops: maize, rice, wheat and soybeans. Although yields continue to increase in many areas, we find that across 24\textendash 39\% of maize-, rice-, wheat- and soybean-growing areas, yields either never improve, stagnate or collapse. This result underscores the challenge of meeting increasing global agricultural demands. New investments in underperforming regions, as well as strategies to continue increasing yields in the high-performing areas, are required.}, copyright = {2012 Nature Publishing Group}, file 